<div id="review_25309548" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/25309548" />
    <a title="Joyce" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1234669-joyce"><img alt="Joyce" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1416982107p2/1234669.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/25309548?book_show_action=true">Jun 24, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joyce" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joyce" href="/user/show/1234669-joyce">Joyce</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer25309548" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17623436354485346818">I decided to re-read this since it had been at least 15 years since I first read it and I remembered it not one whit (that says more about me than it does the novel). Yet there are Cliffs Notes on it now?! Arrgh! A friend of mine who teaches with me also admitted that she got tired of teaching the Joy Luck Club, so she started teaching this one instead because many of the same themes are explored.<br/><br/>I&apos;d agree it&apos;s every bit as satisfying as the Joy Luck Club, although if I had to choose between the</span>
  <span id="freeText17623436354485346818" style="display:none">I decided to re-read this since it had been at least 15 years since I first read it and I remembered it not one whit (that says more about me than it does the novel). Yet there are Cliffs Notes on it now?! Arrgh! A friend of mine who teaches with me also admitted that she got tired of teaching the Joy Luck Club, so she started teaching this one instead because many of the same themes are explored.<br /><br />I'd agree it's every bit as satisfying as the Joy Luck Club, although if I had to choose between the two books to be stranded with on a desert island, I'd pick Amy Tan's first novel. I happen to love the alternating viewpoints in that book (which, I fully realize, confused the heck out of some people). The Kitchen God's Wife has a simple framing device and then it's told mostly from a single point of view, so it's less challenging in that regard. But the mother's story is every bit as heart-wrenching and Tan's pen is every bit as talented here. <br /><br />In fact, Amy Tan has written nothing I didn't like EXCEPT for her last novel, Saving Fish From Drowning, which was a total disaster. Hated. It.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17623436354485346818" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


